          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>1 fol. on parchment; Shelfmark: 30.317; Qurʾānic Text: Q 43:76-44:3; Lines per page: 12; Script style: kūfī (type C); Dimensions: 546 x 622 mm; Estimated date of production: uncertain, might be a modern copy. </p>
              <p> </p>
              <p>See information about this fragment on the<ref target="https://www.dia.org/art/collection/object/quran-folio-49343"> website of the Detroit Institute of Arts</ref>. This fragment was mentioned by Eléonore Cellard in a <ref target="https://twitter.com/CellardEleonore/status/1303638076963524610">twitter message</ref> on September 9, 2020.</p>
              <p>  </p>
              <p>Measurements and script style are similar to fragments of a voluminous codex of Egyptian origin kept in Paris, Gotha, Istanbul and Cairo (where apparently - according to the website <ref target="https://www.islamic-awareness.org/quran/text/mss/dak139.html">Islamic Awareness </ref>- more than 300 fol. are preserved - albeit unaccessible - by the Egyptian National Library), see overview in <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/verse-navigator/sura/43/verse/85/manuscripts/171/page/3v">Gotha ms. orient. A 462</ref>.   </p>
              <p>A large part of the Qurʾānic text included in this folio (fol. 1r: Q 43:76 word 2 - Q 43:84 word 4; fol. 1v Q 43:84 word 5 - Q 44:3 word 4) is contained in <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/manuscripts/171/page/3r?sura=43&amp;amp;verse=85">Gotha ms. orient. A 462 fol. 3r</ref> (Q 43:80 word 6 - Q43:85 word 10 ): and <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/manuscripts/171/page/3v?sura=43&amp;amp;verse=85">fol. 3v</ref> (Q 43:52 word 6 - Q 46:15 word 5). This indicates that the folio does not originally belong to the codex. Until September 2020 the page was labelled by the Detroit Institute of Arts,as “Forgery of a Qur'ān Folio, early 20th century”, in February 2022 the website of the museum mentions as date "11th - 12th century". However, the question remains open when this folio was produced; scientific analysis (carbon dating) of the parchment and ink analysis could possibly contribute to  a better understanding of this fragment of the Qurʾān.</p>
            </summary>
